Surveying the Wider Open Innovation Research Domain



Before narrowing our focus, it is helpful to see the open innovation concept as closely intertwined with other growing contemporary areas of research. For example, the tenets of design thinking (see Glen, Suciu, Baughn, and Anson, [47] ) emphasize a deep customer understanding, external observation, and iteration for innovation with a constant focus on the business model. These ideas are all reminiscent of open innovation. Relatedly, the interest in business model innovation has rapidly increased (Chesbrough, [20] ; Massa, Tucci, and Afuah, [75] ) with more recent attention on open business models (Chesbrough, [18] ; Vanhaverbeke and Chesbrough, [104] ). Similarly, within the entrepreneurship literature, there is recent growth in research related to bricolage, which is defined by Senyard, Baker, Steffens, and Davidsson ([91] ) as {\textquotedbl}making do by applying combinations of the [both internal and external] resources at hand to new problems and opportunities.{\textquotedbl} This concept is inherently compatible with open innovation and the supposition that many firms turn to open innovation out of necessity (Lee, Park, Yoon, and Park, [68] ; Van de Vrande, De Jong, Vanhaverbeke, and De Rochemont, [102] ).



