As has been true in other places within the larger innovation literature (Garcia and Calantone, [42] ), there have been numerous definitions of the term open innovation since the concept was introduced (Gianiodis, Ellis, and Secchi [[46] ] identify seven different definitions). According to Dahlander and Gann ([29] ), the most commonly used definition at the time remained Chesbrough's ([17] , p. xxiv) original definition: {\textquotedbl}open innovation is a paradigm that assumes that firms can and should use external ideas as well as internal ideas, and internal and external paths to market, as firms look to advance their technology.{\textquotedbl} Subsequently, Chesbrough's own definition of open innovation has evolved, most recently to: {\textquotedbl}a distributed innovation process based on purposively managed knowledge flows across organizational boundaries, using pecuniary and non-pecuniary mechanisms in line with the organization's business model{\textquotedbl} (Chesbrough and Bogers, [22] , p. 17). A congruent theme in these definitions is that open innovation is a firm-centric approach to innovation--thus distinguishing it from some parts of the user innovation literature (Baldwin and von Hippel, [6] ; Bogers, Afuah, and Bastian, [11] ; Bogers and West, [14] ). Though knowledge may enter the firm from any external source (and conversely, knowledge generated inside the firm can be commercialized by external parties), these definitions restrict open innovation's domain to innovation involving a business model. While a subset of researchers have taken a broader view of open innovation that does not necessitate organizational involvement (see Chesbrough, [21] ), even the more restrictive definitions encompass virtually limitless distinct mechanisms of openness (as illustrated in Table [NaN] ).



